utility model?

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:27.110
In particular, we
discussed three types

00:16:27.110 --> 00:16:29.040
of ways of measuring
risk aversion.

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:30.620
We discuss certainty
equivalents.

00:16:30.620 --> 00:16:32.840
We discussed choices
from gambles.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:35.570
We also discussed
insurance choices.

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:38.250
This is the Sydnor paper.

00:16:38.250 --> 00:16:41.670
And then, we discussed what is
problematic about the estimates

00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:44.760
of risk aversion in the
expected utility model.

00:16:44.760 --> 00:16:46.650
In particular, we
discussed evidence

00:16:46.650 --> 00:16:50.360
that found that there tends to
be substantial small-scale risk

00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:53.075
aversion, so when you
give people small gambles,

00:16:53.075 --> 00:16:54.450
they tend to be
quite risk averse

00:16:54.450 --> 00:16:58.680
or they tend to have a
very quite high gamma.

00:16:58.680 --> 00:17:02.130
But we know also from large
scale choices that the risk

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:06.569
aversion cannot be actually
that high when people make these

00:17:06.569 --> 00:17:07.349
choices.

00:17:07.349 --> 00:17:09.480
People leave the house
every day and engage

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:11.760
in quite a few risks.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:14.250
In the long run, they
hold stocks and so on.

00:17:14.250 --> 00:17:17.430
This must mean
that their long run

00:17:17.430 --> 00:17:20.400
using sort of long-run choices,
that implies essentially

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:22.199
a relatively low gamma.

00:17:22.199 --> 00:17:25.140
But since the expected utility
model only has like one

00:17:25.140 --> 00:17:28.950
parameter, it cannot explain
both of those features and sort

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:30.870
of ignores this trouble.

00:17:30.870 --> 00:17:35.250
So essentially, if you try
to match a small-scale risk

00:17:35.250 --> 00:17:38.650
aversion, then you need to have
a very large gamma, high gamma.

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:40.590
If you try to match
large-scale risk aversion,

00:17:40.590 --> 00:17:42.030
you need to have a low gamma.

00:17:42.030 --> 00:17:45.030
And that sort of brings
trouble, because you can't just

00:17:45.030 --> 00:17:46.770
explain both of those things.

00:17:46.770 --> 00:17:49.440
And sort of Matthew
Rabin in Rabin & Thaler,

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:53.940
as well as recitation 4 discuss
this conundrum and this issue

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:58.370
and in quite a bit of detail.

