00:21:32.210 --> 00:21:34.780
And the question is,
Maddie is writing

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:36.890
a problem set for 14.13.

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:40.440
She gets utility u of q from the
number of questions she writes.

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:42.080
She has reference-dependent
preferences

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:45.953
around the goal of writing
10 questions, with 10

00:21:45.953 --> 00:21:47.870
as her reference points.

00:21:47.870 --> 00:21:51.500
If you normalize the utility
of 10 questions to 0,

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:55.345
which of the following would be
consistent with loss aversion?

00:21:55.345 --> 00:21:56.720
I'll let you have
a look at this.

00:21:56.720 --> 00:22:00.770
So there's option A, u of
of 8 equals minus 2, u of 12

00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:02.660
equals 1.

00:22:02.660 --> 00:22:06.560
And number B, option B yields
8 equals minus 2, u of 12

00:22:06.560 --> 00:22:07.700
equals 2.

00:22:07.700 --> 00:22:13.820
And then C is, option C is u of
8 equals minus 1, and u of 12

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:16.670
equals 2.

00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:20.810
So which of those answers is
consistent with loss aversion?

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:24.050
The answer is option
A. Now, why is that?

00:22:24.050 --> 00:22:28.610
Well, loss aversion sort of
implies that losses hurt more

00:22:28.610 --> 00:22:30.390
than gains help.

00:22:30.390 --> 00:22:32.780
So with preferences
as in A, Maddie

00:22:32.780 --> 00:22:35.810
would have the utility
cost of 2 from falling

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:37.970
short of her goal
of two questions,

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:42.200
but only a gain of 1 util
from exceeding her goal by two

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:43.040
questions, right?

00:22:43.040 --> 00:22:49.050
So the goal of, the
game of exceeding,

00:22:49.050 --> 00:22:54.980
of being by two questions above,
so being two questions above

00:22:54.980 --> 00:22:57.050
gives her some gain of 1 util.

00:22:57.050 --> 00:22:59.240
But the utility costs of
falling short with two

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:00.828
is twice as large,
which just tends

00:23:00.828 --> 00:23:02.495
to be kind of like
the evidence that you

00:23:02.495 --> 00:23:04.040
would see in loss aversion.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:07.450
And the other two examples
don't have that feature.

00:23:07.450 --> 00:23:11.480
So really only answer
number A is correct.

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:15.950
Second question.

00:23:15.950 --> 00:23:19.580
Maddie is walking home and
passes a bakery unexpectedly.

00:23:19.580 --> 00:23:21.140
She decides to buy a pastry.

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:23.060
For example, she
looks at the pastry,

00:23:23.060 --> 00:23:24.650
and it looks really nice.

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:27.740
Prior to purchasing the
pastry, her maximum willingness

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:31.010
to pay for the pastry was P0.

00:23:31.010 --> 00:23:35.030
Then she runs into Alan-- this
is our previous, excellent TA--

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:37.640
who asks to buy the
pastry from her.

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:41.480
She offers him the lowest price
she is willing to accept, P1.

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:44.510
Which of the following
comparisons between P0 and P1

00:23:44.510 --> 00:23:46.910
is consistent with
an endowment effect,

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:52.790
P0 larger than P1, P0 equals
P1, or P0 smaller than P1?

00:23:57.660 --> 00:24:01.320
The answer is answer
number C. Why is that?

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:05.550
Well, the endowment effect
says that people are--

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:10.590
when their willingness to
pay, that is in this case P0,

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:13.800
is smaller than their
willingness to accept,

00:24:13.800 --> 00:24:14.860
when they accept.

00:24:14.860 --> 00:24:18.450
That is to say, being endowed
with an item in this case,

00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:22.320
like a pastry, increases
one's willingness to pay.

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:25.380
That is to say, if somebody
asks you to sell something

00:24:25.380 --> 00:24:27.960
that you own, you
ask for more money

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:30.690
than you're willing to
pay in the first place

00:24:30.690 --> 00:24:32.830
when you don't own the item.

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:36.810
And so the endowment effect
will then predict that,

00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:42.150
or the endowment effect
entails that now P1 is larger

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:46.950
than P0, which is answer
number C. So Maddie values

00:24:46.950 --> 00:24:50.010
the pastry more after
she has bought it,

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:51.520
compared to like
prior to buying it.

