do we typically find in
dictator and ultimatum games?

00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:35.460
For instance, in
dictator games, people

00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:40.020
tend to give something like
20% to 30% of their share.

00:25:40.020 --> 00:25:42.840
People tend to be quite
nice in those games.

00:25:42.840 --> 00:25:46.305
Now, then we discussed then
like given that evidence,

00:25:46.305 --> 00:25:50.720
so given that people look quite
nice in these types of games,

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:53.010
there's also some other
evidence people give

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:55.900
to charity or things like that.

00:25:55.900 --> 00:25:57.720
Do we think that is
evidence of people

00:25:57.720 --> 00:26:02.410
being generally nice to others
because of poor altruism?

00:26:02.410 --> 00:26:04.960
Or if not, why not?

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:08.520
We discussed sort of three
sets of evidence in particular.

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:13.343
We discussed the costly exit or
exit options in dictator games.

00:26:13.343 --> 00:26:15.760
So people essentially won't
be able to leave the dictator.

00:26:15.760 --> 00:26:17.830
They rather sort
of leave and give,

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:19.300
and sort of keep the money.

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:22.690
Or they're willing to pay
some small amount of money

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:24.160
to leave the
dictator game and not

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:26.500
having to face
some other person,

00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:29.320
but it then feel compelled
to give to others.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:33.880
There was the option of
hiding behind the computer.

00:26:33.880 --> 00:26:35.620
If a computer gives
you the option

00:26:35.620 --> 00:26:38.590
to hide behind the computer
to be mean to others,

00:26:38.590 --> 00:26:41.560
you might take advantage of
that and actually be meaner

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:42.780
than you would be otherwise.

00:26:42.780 --> 00:26:46.240
So altruism, or people's giving
tends to go down quite a bit

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:49.960
when they're able to
hide behind the computer.

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:53.040
So both of those types
of pieces of evidence

00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:56.670
are evidence of social image
being important in giving.

00:26:56.670 --> 00:26:59.580
People care a lot about
what others think,

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:01.710
in particular what
others think about them,

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:03.850
and they don't want
to upset others.

00:27:03.850 --> 00:27:09.420
And so if they're able to
avoid those kind of situations,

00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:10.590
they might be able to--

00:27:10.590 --> 00:27:13.230
they might want to do that,
which would suggest that it's

00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:16.650
not really that they want
others to do well in the sense

00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:19.830
that they really want others
to have money or more money

00:27:19.830 --> 00:27:23.500
than before, but rather it's
because of social pressure

00:27:23.500 --> 00:27:26.610
or social image concerns,
people might give

00:27:26.610 --> 00:27:29.580
in dictator or ultimatum games.

00:27:29.580 --> 00:27:32.460
Moreover, there's some
evidence of self-image

00:27:32.460 --> 00:27:37.000
about people caring about what
they think about themselves.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.410
They want to think of themselves
as being a good person.

00:27:40.410 --> 00:27:43.260
And so the evidence of
the moral wiggle room

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:48.270
seems to suggest that these
concerns are quite important.

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:52.890
In particular, people are
engaging in some behavior

00:27:52.890 --> 00:27:57.180
where they delude themselves
that they are in fact nice,

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:59.610
when in reality, they're not.

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:03.810
So that's discussed in
detail in the lecture.

00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:05.435
Again, we will not
